    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The \"goblin in the box\" is actually a pretty common phenomenon in the HVAC industry. It's not meant to be taken literally, but rather a colloquialism used to describe a situation where a loose wire or a faulty component is causing the motor to vibrate and produce the humming noise. It's like a mischievous little goblin that's causing trouble, but it's usually just a simple fix.\n\nIn your case, if the humming noise is coming from the compressor, it's possible that there's a loose wire or a faulty capacitor that's causing the problem. You can try to troubleshoot the issue yourself by checking the connections and looking for any signs of wear or damage. If you're not comfortable with DIY repairs or if you're not sure what you're looking at, it's always best to call a professional repairman. They'll be able to diagnose the issue and make the necessary repairs to get your AC unit up and running smoothly again.\n\nYou know, I was talking to a fellow who's a master electrician, and he told me that sometimes, the humming noise can be caused by a \"goblin's nest\" – a tangle of wires that's causing the motor to vibrate. He said",
